<HEADLINE>
<P>
AGAINST THE CRUNCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thank you for your story on the perfect carrot ("The Quest for the Perfect 
Carrot," Dec. 9). You hit a raw nerve. 
</P>
<P>
 I think it is tragic that this generation will never savor the true flavors of 
our many varied and wonderful vegetables. I am saddened too that our talented, 
dedicated chefs and food writers have succumbed to the fiction that a crunchy 
vegetable is good merely because of its consistency -- disregarding taste. 
</P>
<P>
 The fear of overcooking has replaced good judgment. A certain amount of time 
and vigilance is required for a vegetable to assume its own identity and not 
lose it -- neither celery nor mush. 
</P>
<P>
 Perhaps all is not lost. Your fine article gives one hope. 
</P>
<P>
 -- RHODA HIATT, Los Angeles 
</P>
