<HEADLINE>
<P>
ELAINE KENNEDY, ANAHEIM ARTIST, DIES OF STROKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Elaine Kennedy, an artist who had lived in Anaheim for many years, died Sunday 
of a stroke. She was 54. 
</P>
<P>
 Kennedy was vacationing in Temecula with her husband, Don, when she was 
stricken on the golf course on Dec. 29. 
</P>
<P>
 Active in the now-defunct Torana Art League as well as the Southern California 
Women's Caucus for Art, Kennedy was a painter of vibrant landscapes. She died 
just two days before the opening of her one-woman show, "The River Still 
Flows," at the Theatre Arts Gallery, Concordia University in Irvine. A private 
memorial has been planned for the opening reception Friday night. The 
university is at 1530 Concordia. The show will continue through Jan. 31. 
</P>
<P>
 A breast cancer survivor, Kennedy had "the ability of making people feel she 
knew them forever," a friend said. In addition to her husband, she leaves two 
children, Colleen Premer of Costa Mesa and Craig Kennedy of Huntington Beach, 
and three sisters and two brothers, all of Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
