<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA ANITA; BRILLIANT BLUE WINS FOR FIRST TIME IN 14 MONTHS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL CHRISTINE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With Brilliant Blue, the longest shot in the field at 24-1, winning the 
next-to-last race in Wednesday's pick six at Santa Anita, there were only two 
tickets with all six winners and they were worth $485,636 apiece. Brilliant 
Blue, beating Prince Wild by 1 3/4 lengths, was winless in 10 starts last year. 
</P>
<P>
 Ridden by Alex Solis, Santa Anita's leading jockey, Brilliant Blue won for the 
first time in 14 months, giving trainer Wiz Murdoch his first victory at Santa 
Anita. 
</P>
<P>
 Notes 
</P>
<P>
 Chris Antley rode both halves of the early double, replacing an ailing Pat 
Valenzuela aboard Snoboy in the first race. . . . "Jeff's cerebral pressure is 
much better," trainer Wayne Lukas said of his son and chief assistant, who has 
been in a coma for three weeks since suffering multiple skull fractures while 
trying to flag down a runaway horse at his father's barn. Lukas' condition was 
listed as serious. BILL CHRISTINE 
</P>
</TEXT>
