<P>
 WOMEN STYMIED: Although female golfers make up nearly 40% of the nation's 
total, some clubs still discriminate (A5). . . . At 73-year-old Saticoy Country 
Club, rules that prevented women from playing on Wednesdays or Saturdays were 
eliminated years ago. But traditions persist, said Roma Chandler, former 
president of the Saticoy Women's Golf Assn. . . . "The unwritten rule is 
Tuesday and Friday, women get the first tee-offs, and Wednesday is men's day. 
But it's a lot better than it used to be." 
</P>
<P>
 FAR OUT: As if the Ventura Freeway weren't scary enough, here's a new hazard: 
kidnapers from outer space. Two women driving through Camarillo say they spent 
a couple of hours on a spaceship being ogled by aliens (Ventura County Life, 
Page 18). . . . Abduction reports give similar descriptions of the culprits: 
short, gray, hairless creatures with four-digit hands, dark eyes and tiny 
mouths. 
</P>
<P>
 ROAD SIGN: That new sign for the Thousand Oaks Auto Mall has finally been 
approved (B5), and the builder says it will be a beaut. . . . "It's unlike any 
other auto mall sign you will see anywhere," said Susan Bailey of Signature 
Signs. Highlights: foliage-bedecked pillars supporting a 5 1/2-foot-diameter 
globe, and brass letters hailing the auto mall as the world's largest. . . . 
Motorists drive right past the existing sign without noticing, she said. "Next 
thing they know, they're at the Oxnard Auto Mall." 
