<P>
COUUNTYWIDE FOCUS: CITIES TO GET SAY IN POLLUTION POLICIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TINA DAUNT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Complying with a new state law, the Ventura County Board of Supervisors has 
agreed to give cities a say for the first time in setting county policies 
intended to reduce air pollution. 
</P>
<P>
 The board voted 5 to 0 on Tuesday to appoint city representatives to the Air 
Pollution Control District board, which now includes all five supervisors. 
</P>
<P>
 "The county and the cities together must determine the number of 
representatives," said Richard H. Baldwin, the county's top air pollution 
official.  
</P>
<P>
 Supervisors Vicky Howard and Susan K. Lacey plan to meet with city officials 
within the next few weeks to work out the details. 
</P>
<P>
 If county and city leaders cannot agree on the board's composition before 
July, the law requires that the board be made up of an equal number of county 
and city leaders. TINA DAUNT 
</P>
