<HEADLINE>
<P>
SALTER REJECTS 3RD TERM: 'CHANGE IS IMPORTANT' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By G. JEANETTE AVENT, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Beverly Hills Mayor Maxwell H. Salter announced this week that he will not 
seek reelection to the City Council in April, saying eight years on the council 
is more than enough for any one official.  
</P>
<P>
 Salter, 73, disclosed his retirement plan in a brief speech at the start of 
Tuesday's council meeting. Two seats, the ones held by Salter and Councilman 
Robert K. Tanenbaum, are on the April 12 ballot. 
</P>
<P>
 Salter said his family and supporters had encouraged him to run for a third 
four-year term because he brought business experience to city government, but 
he said he decided it was time for new leaders with new ideas.  
</P>
<P>
 "I am a firm believer in eight years and two terms of service," Salter said. 
"Change is important and healthy. After eight years, we begin to become too 
accepting of conditions, too willing to wait for progress and too much a part 
of the system. Experience is valuable, but fresh new approaches to 
problem-solving revitalize our city government." 
</P>
<P>
 Salter, who received a standing ovation from his council colleagues and people 
in the audience, said that although he will not be a candidate, he has "no 
intention of retreating from involvement in civic affairs." 
</P>
<P>
 Salter is chairman of Beno's Family Fashions, a 55-store clothing chain that 
he built starting with a single Army-Navy store in San Luis Obispo. 
</P>
<P>
 z He was first elected to the council in 1986 and reelected in 1990. He held 
the largely ceremonial post of mayor, which is rotated among the five council 
members, during the 1989-90 and 1993-94 fiscal years. 
</P>
<P>
 He cited among his accomplishments his efforts to make government more 
responsive to residents and his role in the passage of a $77-million school 
bond approved by voters last year.  
</P>
<P>
 Salter's announcement, which came two weeks after the opening of the 
qualifying period for council candidates, ensures that at least one new face 
will appear on the council after the April election. 
</P>
<P>
 To date, seven residents, including incumbent Tanenbaum, have taken out 
nominating papers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
