<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: RETAIL AND RESTAURANTS; HANG 30 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Greg Johnson, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Surfing's up, at least in age. 
</P>
<P>
 Surfing, the San Clemente-based magazine that chronicles the sport of surfing, 
is celebrating its 30th anniversary with three "killer special collectors' 
editions." 
</P>
<P>
 If the first -- chock-full of epic surfing photos -- is any indication, the 
magazines indeed may be worth collecting. Surfing asked greats of yesterday and 
today to determine which photos would grace the issue's pages. 
</P>
<P>
 "This idea had its roots in the fact that every surfer in the world has lived 
a fantasy around the pictures he or she sees in surf mags," Editor-in-Chief 
Nick Carroll said. "Many heroic figures in surfing have felt their first 
twinges of destiny when being awe-struck by an image of a favorite surfer, surf 
spot or wave worth conquering." 
</P>
